article.headline: Wyoming 87, Charlotte 78
article.story: LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- Justin Williams has been saying all along that his role for Wyoming isn't to be the big guy scoring big points. Instead, he's the big guy getting lots of blocks and rebounds. Williams had nine blocks and 20 rebounds in the Cowboys' 87-78 win over Charlotte for third place Tuesday in the Black Coaches Association Invitational. Both were tournament records. Williams had a standout game despite a late-October knee sprain that cost him a couple weeks of practice and one of the Cowboys' two exhibition games. "He gave a warrior-like effort," Wyoming coach Steve McClain said. "You're talking about a guy who didn't practice for two weeks and then only one week before this." The Cowboys (2-1) had a better night shooting against the 49ers (1-2) than they did in a 62-59 overtime loss to North Carolina-Wilmington on Monday. In that game, 32 of Wyoming's points were made on free throws -- and 65-percent free-throw shooting at that. "The game had some flow," McClain said of the Charlotte game. "You could actually drive it and kick it." Steve Leven led the Cowboys with 16 points, followed by Williams with 13. Brad Jones added 12 and Kevin Lewis 10. Charlotte trailed by as much as 67-48 about midway through the second half. But the 49ers got back into the game with help from four 3-pointers by Curtis Withers. Charlotte narrowed the score to 82-77 on a 3-pointer by De'Angelo Alexander and a basket by Withers. Wyoming, meanwhile, hit 1 of 8 in four free-throw appearances. "We've got to finish better. I'm going to bring in a free-throw coach," McClain said. Each team made one of two free throws to make the score 83-78. The 49ers then called time out -- but they had no time outs left, sending Leven to the line to make two. Jones added two more free throws for Wyoming for the final score. "You have to give them credit," Charlotte coach Bobby Lutz said. "Especially Williams, because he's such a game-changer inside." The Cowboys outshot Charlotte 56 percent to 31 percent from the field. The 49ers were led by Withers with 25 points, followed by De'Angelo with 21. Withers and Chris Nance each had 15 rebounds. "We got outcoached again," Lutz said. "They played better than we did." McClain said he was particuarly impressed with his younger players, such as Jarrod Boswell, a sophomore center who scored 10 points in his first regular-season Division I game. "I like our young kids. They're only going to get better," he said. Wyoming led 45-30 at the half. In the first half, Charlotte shot 27 percent and was 0-9 on 3-pointers, while the Cowboys were 58 percent and 5-10 from 3-point range. Wyoming pulled ahead 12-6 on baskets by Leven, Williams and Daaron Brown. The 49ers pulled back within 15-12 on a scoring rebound by Antwon Coleman, but the Cowboys widened their lead to 22-12 and then 29-14.
